lyze the impact of identification requirement laws, proof-of-citizenship requirements, felony disenfranchisement, and gerrymandering. Before 2020, the impact of the laws leaned slightly negative but was mixed. More recent developments, however, point to a far more alarming implication—widespread belief in factually-baseless allegations of fraud, which undermines Americans' trust and faith in our constitutional democracy; these allegations reached a crescendo in 2021 as a violent mob seized the US Capitol. The book concludes with an afterword on the 2020 elections and their aftermath.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxSuffragexHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxSuffragezMississippixHistory. 0aGerrymanderingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSuffragezUnited StatesxStatesxHistory. 0aVoter registrationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aVoter suppressionzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : American Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aSociology : Sociology of Law. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooker, Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHann, Deborah G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollenbeck, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRackaway, Chapman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelby, Bekah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Michael A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.